<br>
As much as I totally support single groups being able to get loot they can actually loot, I think there are serious problems with the way it's done on ldon.<br>
<br>
First, yes I'd agree that the stuff you can buy with less than 500 AP is teh suck. However usually in everquest, getting linear upgrades will require exponential efforts. by that I mean that getting a 140 hp upgrade will require beating an encounter that is far more than twice as difficult as getting a 70 hp item. This is fine, because player character power also increase exponentially with levels.<br>
<br>
Not so in ldon. With 1492 pts, you get VT+ quality loot. While the rewards at 700-800 AP are probably appropriate for doing a long string of relatively trivial encounters at normal difficulty, I am not quite sure getting VT loot is appropriate for simply working on encounters that is more or less of plane of valor difficulty.<br>
<br>
Maybe there should be a progression in what you stuff you can buy. Like the very best stuff might be only purchasable with points acquired in hard missions, or &quot;unlocked&quot; only after you have completed a certain number of hard missions, like it's the case now with dungeon requirements for certain items.<br>
<br>
Because let's face it... once you work out the tweaks and you don't get nailed by bugs the normal difficulty encounters aren't challenging. I know not everyone is as well equipped, but sunday we did a whole dungeon with our shadowkight life tapping because our cleric went ld and couldn't log back. I know he is particularly well equipped, but this is sad.<br>
<br>
Once again I am all for groups getting good loot they can use. But the current system isn't balanced. I'd say decrease the costs on items so it's more in line with time invested (it takes too long presently), and make tiers of items available only when you get a certain amount of points at certain level of difficulties. And add a medium difficulty level (make current &quot;normal&quot; as &quot;easy&quot;, because that's what is is right now), so that people can have a smoother progression instead of going from the trivial current normal level to the hellishly difficult hard (which is fine as it is btw except it needs 150 AP instead of 76).<br>
<br>
